Kristian Nielsen>   mysqlbinlog_max_binlog_statement_size.patch

I looked at this patch. Unfortunately, the patch has a serious bug, so it is
not suitable for merging as it is.

I have attached a test case which causes the server to crash with the patch
applied (I'm quite sure the problem will also be seen in Percona Server).

The problem is with multi-table UPDATE and DELETE queries. In this case, the
binlog events look like this:

   <Table map for table t1>
   <Table map for table t2>
   <Update_rows_log_event for rows in table t1>
   <Update_rows_log_event for rows in table t2>

But when the –binlog-stmt-max-size option is used to split a BINLOG statement
output from mysqlbinlog, the code handles this case incorrectly. The second
and subsequent splitted BINLOG statements have only the first table map, any
other are discarded:

   <Table map for table t1>
   <Update_rows_log_event for rows in table t1>
   <Update_rows_log_event for rows in table t2>

This obviously fails when run on the server.

So the patch is rejected as is. Can a developer from Percona take a look and
make the appropriate fix for this issue? Then I can take another look at
merging the patch.

[In fact, this patch triggers another crash, hitting this assert in the patch
row_based_replication_without_primary_key.patch in find_key():

   DBUG_ASSERT(m_table && m_table->in_use != NULL);

(m_table is NULL in this case).

I don't fully understand how m_table->in_use works, but I wonder why this
assert was put in place? Maybe it's just the assert that is wrong. Or maybe
it's a consequence of the above problem.]

 - Kristian.


