I think this function should not kill transaction that only contain "SELECT", because "SELECT" command needn't lock.
Only if the transaction contain "UPDATE/DELTE/INSERT" and not type "COMMIT" a long time, it must be killed.

I modified source code on our system(Percona 5.1.59-13.0), I add "uint16 is_have_lock_thd" on class THD, it record this Thread contain "UPDATE/DELETE/INSERT" or not, default value is 0 (not contain). I init it on THD::THD, add "is_have_lock_thd =0;".

And I update this value on function mysql_execute_command, only if the query is "UPDATE/DELTE/INSERT", I update the is_have_lock_thd. Then if the is_have_lock_thd = 1, I can consider the thread is contain MODIFY query, it must be killed if timeout.
  if (lex->sql_command == SQLCOM_UPDATE
          || lex->sql_command == SQLCOM_UPDATE_MULTI
          || lex->sql_command == SQLCOM_DELETE
          || lex->sql_command == SQLCOM_DELETE_MULTI
          || lex->sql_command == SQLCOM_INSERT
          || lex->sql_command == SQLCOM_INSERT_SELECT ) {
    thd->is_have_lock_thd = 1;
  } else if (lex->sql_command == SQLCOM_COMMIT) {
      thd->is_have_lock_thd = 0;
  }

And in function thd_kill, I changed "if (tmp->command == COM_DAEMON)" to "if (tmp->command == COM_DAEMON || tmp->is_have_lock_thd == 0 )". So I will not killed thread only contain SELECT.

while ((tmp=it++))
    {
        if (tmp->command == COM_DAEMON || tmp->is_have_lock_thd == 0 )
            continue;
        if (tmp->thread_id == id)
        {
            pthread_mutex_lock(&tmp->LOCK_thd_data);
            break;
        }
    }

I think this is more suitable.

